Comment: I did my normal opening.
He attacked my pawn with his queen's pawn.
I decided to take the pawn.
He obviously took my pawn.
I attempted to make him retreat his queen by getting my knight out.
He checked me with his queen.
I blocked the check with my bishop.
He got his bishop out. At this point, it looked like he had the control of the centre of the board.
I decided to attack his queen with my pawn so that I could move my bishop from the line of check.
I couldn't as he only moved his queen one square back.
That is when I began to get my pieces out a bit more.
He attacked my knight so if he took it, I would have to take the bishop with my pawn rather than my bishop because my bishop is pinned.
To stop my bishop being pinned, I castled.
He swaped of his bishop for my knight.
I took his bishop. At the same time I was threatening to take his rook.
To stop that he moved his pawn to c6.
I moved my pawn one forward so that I was attacking his queen and pawn at the same time.
He moved his queen away so it could not be taken.
I took his pawn.
He took my pawn back.
